<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t17511016-12">
               <interp inst="t17511016-12" type="collection" value="BAILEY"></interp>
               <interp inst="t17511016-12" type="year" value="1751"></interp>
               <interp inst="t17511016-12" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/17511016"></interp>
               <interp inst="t17511016-12" type="date" value="17511016"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t17511016-12-off59-c84" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-defend103 t17511016-12-off59 t17511016-12-verdict64"></join>
         
               <p>555. (L.) 
               
                  <persName id="t17511016-12-defend103" type="defendantName">
                     Mary 
                     Johnson 
                  <interp inst="t17511016-12-defend103" type="surname" value="Johnson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-defend103" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-defend103" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
            , <rs id="t17511016-12-deflabel58" type="occupation">spinster</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-defend103 t17511016-12-deflabel58"></join>, was indicted for <rs id="t17511016-12-off59" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-off59" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-off59" type="offenceSubcategory" value="grandLarceny"></interp>
               stealing one silver spoon, value 10 s.
            </rs> the property of 
               
                  <persName id="t17511016-12-victim105" type="victimName">
                     Samuel 
                     Rogers 
                  <interp inst="t17511016-12-victim105" type="surname" value="Rogers"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-victim105" type="given" value="Samuel"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-victim105" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-off59 t17511016-12-victim105"></join>
                  </persName>
                
            , <rs id="t17511016-12-cd60" type="crimeDate">Sept. 28</rs>
                  <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-off59 t17511016-12-cd60"></join>.* </p>
               <p>Samuel Rogers. I <rs id="t17511016-12-viclabel61" type="occupation">keep a publickhouse</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-victim105 t17511016-12-viclabel61"></join> in <placeName id="t17511016-12-crimeloc62">Old Bedlam</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t17511016-12-crimeloc62" type="placeName" value="Old Bedlam"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t17511016-12-crimeloc62" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-off59 t17511016-12-crimeloc62"></join>. The silver spoon had been in use, I wiped it, put it into the bar, and went down to draw a tankard of beer, leaving the prisoner in the house, but when I came up she was gone, and the spoon missing. I being a <rs id="t17511016-12-viclabel63" type="occupation">parish officer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-victim105 t17511016-12-viclabel63"></join>, went the next day to the workhouse, telling them the affair, and desiring, if such a thing should be heard<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="175110160008"></xptr> of, they would let me know, &amp;c. The next day the spoon was stopped in Smock-alley, at one Mr. Eakins's ; one 
               <persName id="t17511016-12-person106">
                  Mary 
                  Cooper 
               <interp inst="t17511016-12-person106" type="surname" value="Cooper"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person106" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person106" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             carried it there. I went and found her; she told me she had it of the prisoner: then I took up the prisoner, and she owned she stole it while I went down for a tankard of beer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17511016-12-person107">
                  Thomas 
                  Eakins 
               <interp inst="t17511016-12-person107" type="surname" value="Eakins"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person107" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person107" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This spoon was brought to me by one Cooper, who said first it was her own, then that she had it of the prisoner at the bar. I asked her where she lived, she replied here, there, and every where ; so I stopped the spoon, in order to have it advertised.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17511016-12-person108">
                  Mary 
                  Cooper 
               <interp inst="t17511016-12-person108" type="surname" value="Cooper"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person108" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person108" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . This 
               <persName id="t17511016-12-person109">
                  Mary 
                  Johnson 
               <interp inst="t17511016-12-person109" type="surname" value="Johnson"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person109" type="given" value="Mary"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-person109" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             brought this spoon to me, and asked me to pledge it, saying it was a friend's over the water. She was with me at the door when I went to Mr. Eakins's house with me.</p>
               <p>[The spoon produced, and deposed to by the three witnesses]</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>If there were no receivers there would be no thieves. She received the spoon, though I stole it. There is an officer indeed! The officers belonging to Bishopsgate will not give me any relief, which makes me lie about. This man said I might go a whoring or thieving, he did not care how I got my bread.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17511016-12-verdict64" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-verdict64" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-verdict64" type="verdictSubcategory" value="theftunder1s"></interp>
               Guilty, 10 d.
            </rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17511016-12-punish65" type="punishmentDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17511016-12-punish65" type="punishmentCategory" value="transport"></interp>
                     <join result="defendantPunishment" targOrder="Y" targets="t17511016-12-defend103 t17511016-12-punish65"></join>
               
                     <note>[Transportation. See summary.]</note>
               
                  </rs>
               </p>
            </div1>
